<!--html_preserve-->


<p>This tutorial covers downloading NEON data, using the Data Portal and
either the neonUtilities R package or the neonutilities Python package,
as well as basic instruction in beginning to explore and work with the
downloaded data, including guidance in navigating data documentation. We
will explore data of 3 different types, and make a simple figure from
each.</p>
<div id="neon-data" class="section level2">
<h2>NEON data</h2>
<p>There are 3 basic categories of NEON data:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Remote sensing (AOP) - Data collected by the airborne observation
platform, e.g. LIDAR, surface reflectance</li>
<li>Observational (OS) - Data collected by a human in the field, or in
an analytical laboratory, e.g. beetle identification, foliar
isotopes</li>
<li>Instrumentation (IS) - Data collected by an automated, streaming
sensor, e.g.  net radiation, soil carbon dioxide. This category also
includes the surface-atmosphere exchange (SAE) data, which are processed
and structured in a unique way, distinct from other instrumentation data
(see the introductory
<a href="https://www.neonscience.org/eddy-data-intro" target="_blank">eddy
flux data tutorial</a> for details).</li>
</ol>
<p>This lesson covers all three types of data. The download procedures
are similar for all types, but data navigation differs significantly by
type.</p>
</div>
<div id="ds-objectives" markdown="1">
<div id="objectives" class="section level2">
<h2>Objectives</h2>
<p>After completing this activity, you will be able to:</p>
<ul>
<li>Download NEON data using the neonUtilities package.</li>
<li>Understand downloaded data sets and load them into R or Python for
analyses.</li>
</ul>
</div>

<h2>Things You’ll Need To Complete This Tutorial</h2>
<p>You can follow either the R or Python code throughout this tutorial.
* For R users, we recommend using R version 4+ and RStudio. * For Python
users, we recommend using Python 3.9+.</p>
</div>

<div id="getting-started-download-data-from-the-portal" class="section level2">
<h2>Getting started: Download data from the Portal</h2>
<p>Go to the <a href="http://data.neonscience.org" target="_blank">NEON
Data Portal</a> and download some data! To follow the tutorial exactly,
download Photosynthetically active radiation (PAR) (DP1.00024.001) data
from September-November 2019 at Wind River Experimental Forest (WREF).
The downloaded file should be a zip file named NEON_par.zip.</p>
<p>If you prefer to explore a different data product, you can still
follow this tutorial. But it will be easier to understand the steps in
the tutorial, particularly the data navigation, if you choose a sensor
data product for this section.</p>
<p>Once you’ve downloaded a zip file of data from the portal, switch
over to R or Python to proceed with coding.</p>
</div>
<div id="stack-the-downloaded-data-files-stackbytable" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2 class="tabset">Stack the downloaded data files: stackByTable()</h2>
<p>The <code>stackByTable()</code> (or <code>stack_by_table()</code>)
function will unzip and join the files in the downloaded zip file.</p>
<div id="r-2" class="section level3">
<h3>R</h3>
<pre class="r"><code># Modify the file path to match the path to your zip file
stackByTable(&quot;~/Downloads/NEON_par.zip&quot;)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-2" class="section level3">
<h3>Python</h3>
<pre class="python"><code># Modify the file path to match the path to your zip file
nu.stack_by_table(os.path.expanduser(&quot;~/Downloads/NEON_par.zip&quot;))</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-2" class="section level2 unnumbered">
<h2 class="unnumbered"></h2>
<p>In the directory where the zipped file was saved, you should now have
an unzipped folder of the same name. When you open this you will see a
new folder called <strong>stackedFiles</strong>, which should contain at
least seven files: <strong>PARPAR_30min.csv</strong>,
<strong>PARPAR_1min.csv</strong>, <strong>sensor_positions.csv</strong>,
<strong>variables_00024.csv</strong>, <strong>readme_00024.txt</strong>,
<strong>issueLog_00024.csv</strong>, and
<strong>citation_00024_RELEASE-202X.txt</strong>.</p>
</div>
<div id="navigate-data-downloads-is" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2 class="tabset">Navigate data downloads: IS</h2>
<p>Let’s start with a brief description of each file. This set of files
is typical of a NEON IS data product.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>PARPAR_30min.csv</strong>: PAR data at 30-minute averaging
intervals</li>
<li><strong>PARPAR_1min.csv</strong>: PAR data at 1-minute averaging
intervals</li>
<li><strong>sensor_positions.csv</strong>: The physical location of each
sensor collecting PAR measurements. There is a PAR sensor at each level
of the WREF tower, and this table lets you connect the tower level index
to the height of the sensor in meters.</li>
<li><strong>variables_00024.csv</strong>: Definitions and units for each
data field in the PARPAR_#min tables.</li>
<li><strong>readme_00024.txt</strong>: Basic information about the PAR
data product.</li>
<li><strong>issueLog_00024.csv</strong>: A record of known issues
associated with PAR data.</li>
<li><strong>citation_00024_RELEASE-202X.txt</strong>: The citation to
use when you publish a paper using these data, in BibTeX format.</li>
</ul>
<p>We’ll explore the 30-minute data. To read the file, use the function
<code>readTableNEON()</code> or <code>read_table_neon()</code>, which
uses the variables file to assign data types to each column of data:</p>
<div id="r-3" class="section level3">
<h3>R</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>par30 &lt;- readTableNEON(
  dataFile=&quot;~/Downloads/NEON_par_R/stackedFiles/PARPAR_30min.csv&quot;, 
  varFile=&quot;~/Downloads/NEON_par_R/stackedFiles/variables_00024.csv&quot;)
head(par30)</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>par30 &lt;- readTableNEON(
  dataFile=&quot;~/Downloads/NEON_par/stackedFiles/PARPAR_30min.csv&quot;, 
  varFile=&quot;~/Downloads/NEON_par/stackedFiles/variables_00024.csv&quot;)
head(par30)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-3" class="section level3">
<h3>Python</h3>
<pre class="python"><code>
par30 = nu.read_table_neon(
  data_file=os.path.expanduser(
    &quot;~/Downloads/NEON_par/stackedFiles/PARPAR_30min.csv&quot;), 
  var_file=os.path.expanduser(
    &quot;~/Downloads/NEON_par/stackedFiles/variables_00024.csv&quot;))
# Open the par30 table in the table viewer of your choice</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-3" class="section level2 unnumbered">
<h2 class="unnumbered"></h2>
<p>The first four columns are added by <code>stackByTable()</code> when
it merges files across sites, months, and tower heights. The column
<code>publicationDate</code> is the date-time stamp indicating when the
data were published, and the <code>release</code> column indicates which
NEON data release the data belong to. For more information about NEON
data releases, see the
<a href="https://www.neonscience.org/data-samples/data-management/data-revisions-releases" target="_blank">Data
Product Revisions and Releases</a> page.</p>
<p>Information about each data column can be found in the variables
file, where you can see definitions and units for each column of
data.</p>
<div id="plot-par-data" class="section level3 tabset">
<h3 class="tabset">Plot PAR data</h3>
<p>Now that we know what we’re looking at, let’s plot PAR from the top
tower level. We’ll use the mean PAR from each averaging interval, and we
can see from the sensor positions file that the vertical index 080
corresponds to the highest tower level. To explore the sensor positions
data in more depth, see the
<a href="https://www.neonscience.org/resources/learning-hub/tutorials/neon-spatial-data-basics" target="_blank">spatial
data</a> tutorial.</p>
<div id="r-4" class="section level4">
<h4>R</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>plot(PARMean~endDateTime, 
     data=par30[which(par30$verticalPosition==&quot;080&quot;),],
     type=&quot;l&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="504" /></p>
</div>
<div id="python-4" class="section level4">
<h4>Python</h4>
<pre class="python"><code>par30top = par30[par30.verticalPosition==&quot;080&quot;]
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(par30top.endDateTime, par30top.PARMean)
plt.show()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-4" class="section level3 unnumbered">
<h3 class="unnumbered"></h3>
<p>Looks good! The sun comes up and goes down every day, and some days
are cloudy.</p>
</div>
<div id="plot-more-par-data" class="section level3 tabset">
<h3 class="tabset">Plot more PAR data</h3>
<p>To see another layer of data, add PAR from a lower tower level to the
plot.</p>
<div id="r-5" class="section level4">
<h4>R</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>plot(PARMean~endDateTime, 
     data=par30[which(par30$verticalPosition==&quot;080&quot;),],
     type=&quot;l&quot;)

lines(PARMean~endDateTime, 
     data=par30[which(par30$verticalPosition==&quot;020&quot;),],
     col=&quot;blue&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="504" /></p>
</div>
<div id="python-5" class="section level4">
<h4>Python</h4>
<pre class="python"><code>par30low = par30[par30.verticalPosition==&quot;020&quot;]
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(par30top.endDateTime, par30top.PARMean)
ax.plot(par30low.endDateTime, par30low.PARMean)
plt.show()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-5" class="section level3 unnumbered">
<h3 class="unnumbered"></h3>
<p>We can see there is a lot of light attenuation through the
canopy.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="download-files-and-load-directly-to-r-loadbyproduct" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2 class="tabset">Download files and load directly to R:
loadByProduct()</h2>
<p>At the start of this tutorial, we downloaded data from the NEON data
portal. NEON also provides an API, and the <code>neonUtilities</code>
packages provide methods for downloading programmatically in R.</p>
<p>The steps we carried out above - downloading from the portal,
stacking the downloaded files, and reading in to R or Python - can all
be carried out in one step by the neonUtilities function
<code>loadByProduct()</code>.</p>
<p>To get the same PAR data we worked with above, we would run this line
of code using <code>loadByProduct()</code>:</p>
<div id="r-6" class="section level3">
<h3>R</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>parlist &lt;- loadByProduct(dpID=&quot;DP1.00024.001&quot;, 
                         site=&quot;WREF&quot;, 
                         startdate=&quot;2019-09&quot;,
                         enddate=&quot;2019-11&quot;)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-6" class="section level3">
<h3>Python</h3>
<pre class="python"><code>parlist = nu.load_by_product(dpid=&quot;DP1.00024.001&quot;, 
                site=&quot;WREF&quot;, 
                startdate=&quot;2019-09&quot;,
                enddate=&quot;2019-11&quot;)</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-6" class="section level2 unnumbered">
<h2 class="unnumbered"></h2>
<div id="explore-loaded-data" class="section level3">
<h3>Explore loaded data</h3>
<p>The object returned by <code>loadByProduct()</code> in R is a named
list, and the object returned by <code>load_by_product()</code> in
Python is a dictionary. The objects contained in the list or dictionary
are the same set of tables we ended with after stacking the data from
the portal above. You can see this by checking the names of the tables
in <code>parlist</code>:</p>
<div id="r-7" class="section level4">
<h4>R</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>names(parlist)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;citation_00024_RELEASE-2024&quot; &quot;issueLog_00024&quot;             
## [3] &quot;PARPAR_1min&quot;                 &quot;PARPAR_30min&quot;               
## [5] &quot;readme_00024&quot;                &quot;sensor_positions_00024&quot;     
## [7] &quot;variables_00024&quot;</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-7" class="section level4">
<h4>Python</h4>
<pre class="python"><code>parlist.keys()</code></pre>
<pre><code>## dict_keys([&#39;PARPAR_1min&#39;, &#39;PARPAR_30min&#39;, &#39;citation_00024_RELEASE-2024&#39;, &#39;issueLog_00024&#39;, &#39;readme_00024&#39;, &#39;sensor_positions_00024&#39;, &#39;variables_00024&#39;])</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-7" class="section level3 unnumbered">
<h3 class="unnumbered"></h3>
<p>Now let’s walk through the details of the inputs and options in
<code>loadByProduct()</code>.</p>
<p>This function downloads data from the NEON API, merges the
site-by-month files, and loads the resulting data tables into the
programming environment, assigning each data type to the appropriate
class. This is a popular choice for NEON data users because it ensures
you’re always working with the latest data, and it ends with
ready-to-use tables. However, if you use it in a workflow you run
repeatedly, keep in mind it will re-download the data every time. See
below for suggestions on saving the data locally to save time and
compute resources.</p>
<p><code>loadByProduct()</code> works on most observational (OS) and
sensor (IS) data, but not on surface-atmosphere exchange (SAE) data,
remote sensing (AOP) data, and some of the data tables in the microbial
data products. For functions that download AOP data, see the final
section in this tutorial. For functions that work with SAE data, see the
<a href="https://www.neonscience.org/eddy-data-intro" target="_blank">NEON
eddy flux data tutorial</a>.</p>
<p>The inputs to <code>loadByProduct()</code> control which data to
download and how to manage the processing:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>dpID</code>: the data product ID, e.g. DP1.00002.001</li>
<li><code>site</code>: defaults to “all”, meaning all sites with
available data; can be a vector of 4-letter NEON site codes, e.g. 
<code>c(&quot;HARV&quot;,&quot;CPER&quot;,&quot;ABBY&quot;)</code> (or
<code>[&quot;HARV&quot;,&quot;CPER&quot;,&quot;ABBY&quot;]</code> in Python)</li>
<li><code>startdate</code> and <code>enddate</code>: defaults to NA,
meaning all dates with available data; or a date in the form YYYY-MM,
e.g.  2017-06. Since NEON data are provided in month packages, finer
scale querying is not available. Both start and end date are
inclusive.</li>
<li><code>package</code>: either basic or expanded data package.
Expanded data packages generally include additional information about
data quality, such as chemical standards and quality flags. Not every
data product has an expanded package; if the expanded package is
requested but there isn’t one, the basic package will be
downloaded.</li>
<li><code>timeIndex</code>: defaults to “all”, to download all data; or
the number of minutes in the averaging interval. Only applicable to IS
data.</li>
<li><code>release</code>: Specify a NEON data release to download.
Defaults to the most recent release plus provisional data. See the
<a href="https://www.neonscience.org/resources/learning-hub/tutorials/release-provisional-tutorial" target="_blank">release
tutorial</a> for more information.</li>
<li><code>include.provisional</code>: T or F: should Provisional data be
included in the download? Defaults to F to return only Released data,
which are citable by a DOI and do not change over time. Provisional data
are subject to change.</li>
<li><code>check.size</code>: T or F: should the function pause before
downloading data and warn you about the size of your download? Defaults
to T; if you are using this function within a script or batch process
you will want to set it to F.</li>
<li><code>token</code>: Optional NEON API token for faster downloads.
See
<a href="https://www.neonscience.org/resources/learning-hub/tutorials/neon-api-tokens-tutorial" target="_blank">this
tutorial</a> for instructions on using a token.</li>
<li><code>nCores</code>: Number of cores to use for parallel processing.
Defaults to 1, i.e. no parallelization. Only available in R.</li>
<li><code>forceParallel</code>: If the data volume to be processed does
not meet minimum requirements to run in parallel, this overrides. Only
available in R.</li>
<li><code>progress</code>: Set to False to turn off the progress bar.
Only available in Python.</li>
<li><code>cloud_mode</code>: Can be set to True if you are working in a
cloud environment; enables more efficient data transfer from NEON’s
cloud storage. Only available in Python.</li>
</ul>
<p>The <code>dpID</code> is the data product identifier of the data you
want to download. The DPID can be found on the
<a href="http://data.neonscience.org/data-products/explore" target="_blank">
Explore Data Products page</a>. It will be in the form DP#.#####.###</p>
</div>
<div id="download-observational-data" class="section level3 tabset">
<h3 class="tabset">Download observational data</h3>
<p>To explore observational data, we’ll download aquatic plant chemistry
data (DP1.20063.001) from three lake sites: Prairie Lake (PRLA), Suggs
Lake (SUGG), and Toolik Lake (TOOK).</p>
<div id="r-8" class="section level4">
<h4>R</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>apchem &lt;- loadByProduct(dpID=&quot;DP1.20063.001&quot;, 
                  site=c(&quot;PRLA&quot;,&quot;SUGG&quot;,&quot;TOOK&quot;), 
                  package=&quot;expanded&quot;,
                  release=&quot;RELEASE-2024&quot;,
                  check.size=F)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-8" class="section level4">
<h4>Python</h4>
<pre class="python"><code>apchem = nu.load_by_product(dpid=&quot;DP1.20063.001&quot;, 
                  site=[&quot;PRLA&quot;, &quot;SUGG&quot;, &quot;TOOK&quot;], 
                  package=&quot;expanded&quot;,
                  release=&quot;RELEASE-2024&quot;,
                  check_size=False)</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-8" class="section level3 unnumbered">
<h3 class="unnumbered"></h3>
</div>
</div>
<div id="navigate-data-downloads-os" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2 class="tabset">Navigate data downloads: OS</h2>
<p>As we saw above, the object returned by <code>loadByProduct()</code>
is a named list of data frames. Let’s check out what’s the same and
what’s different from the IS data tables.</p>
<div id="r-9" class="section level3">
<h3>R</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>names(apchem)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  [1] &quot;apl_biomass&quot;                       &quot;apl_clipHarvest&quot;                  
##  [3] &quot;apl_plantExternalLabDataPerSample&quot; &quot;apl_plantExternalLabQA&quot;           
##  [5] &quot;asi_externalLabPOMSummaryData&quot;     &quot;categoricalCodes_20063&quot;           
##  [7] &quot;citation_20063_RELEASE-2024&quot;       &quot;issueLog_20063&quot;                   
##  [9] &quot;readme_20063&quot;                      &quot;validation_20063&quot;                 
## [11] &quot;variables_20063&quot;</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-9" class="section level3">
<h3>Python</h3>
<pre class="python"><code>apchem.keys()</code></pre>
<pre><code>## dict_keys([&#39;apl_biomass&#39;, &#39;apl_clipHarvest&#39;, &#39;apl_plantExternalLabDataPerSample&#39;, &#39;apl_plantExternalLabQA&#39;, &#39;asi_externalLabPOMSummaryData&#39;, &#39;categoricalCodes_20063&#39;, &#39;citation_20063_RELEASE-2024&#39;, &#39;issueLog_20063&#39;, &#39;readme_20063&#39;, &#39;validation_20063&#39;, &#39;variables_20063&#39;])</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-9" class="section level2 unnumbered">
<h2 class="unnumbered"></h2>
<div id="explore-tables" class="section level3 tabset">
<h3 class="tabset">Explore tables</h3>
<p>As with the sensor data, we have some data tables and some metadata
tables. Most of the metadata files are the same as the sensor data:
<strong>readme</strong>, <strong>variables</strong>,
<strong>issueLog</strong>, and <strong>citation</strong>. These files
contain the same type of metadata here that they did in the IS data
product. Let’s look at the other files:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>apl_clipHarvest</strong>: Data from the clip harvest
collection of aquatic plants</li>
<li><strong>apl_biomass</strong>: Biomass data from the collected
plants</li>
<li><strong>apl_plantExternalLabDataPerSample</strong>: Chemistry data
from the collected plants</li>
<li><strong>apl_plantExternalLabQA</strong>: Quality assurance data from
the chemistry analyses</li>
<li><strong>asi_externalLabPOMSummaryData</strong>: Quality metrics from
the chemistry lab</li>
<li><strong>validation_20063</strong>: For observational data, a major
method for ensuring data quality is to control data entry. This file
contains information about the data ingest rules applied to each input
data field.</li>
<li><strong>categoricalCodes_20063</strong>: Definitions of each value
for categorical data, such as growth form and sample condition</li>
</ul>
<p>You can work with these tables from the named list object, but many
people find it easier to extract each table from the list and work with
it as an independent object. To do this, use the <code>list2env()</code>
function in R or <code>globals().update()</code> in Python:</p>
<div id="r-10" class="section level4">
<h4>R</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>list2env(apchem, .GlobalEnv)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## &lt;environment: R_GlobalEnv&gt;</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-10" class="section level4">
<h4>Python</h4>
<pre class="python"><code>
globals().update(apchem)</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-10" class="section level3 unnumbered">
<h3 class="unnumbered"></h3>
</div>
<div id="save-data-locally" class="section level3 tabset">
<h3 class="tabset">Save data locally</h3>
<p>Keep in mind that using <code>loadByProduct()</code> will re-download
the data every time you run your code. In some cases this may be
desirable, but it can be a waste of time and compute resources. To come
back to these data without re-downloading, you’ll want to save the
tables locally. The most efficient option is to save the named list in
total.</p>
<div id="r-11" class="section level4">
<h4>R</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>saveRDS(apchem, 
        &quot;~/Downloads/aqu_plant_chem.rds&quot;)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-11" class="section level4">
<h4>Python</h4>
<pre class="p"><code>
# There are a variety of ways to do this in Python; NEON
# doesn&#39;t currently have a specific recommendation. If 
# you don&#39;t have a data-saving workflow you already use, 
# we suggest you check out the pickle module.
</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-11" class="section level3 unnumbered">
<h3 class="unnumbered"></h3>
<p>Then you can re-load the object to a programming environment any
time.</p>
<p>Other options for saving data locally:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Similar to the workflow we started this tutorial with, but using
<code>neonUtilities</code> to download instead of the Portal: Use
<code>zipsByProduct()</code> and <code>stackByTable()</code> instead of
<code>loadByProduct()</code>. With this option, use the function
<code>readTableNEON()</code> to read the files, to get the same column
type assignment that <code>loadByProduct()</code> carries out. Details
can be found in our
<a href="https://www.neonscience.org/neonDataStackR" target="_blank">neonUtilities
tutorial</a>.</li>
<li>Try out the community-developed <code>neonstore</code> package,
which is designed for maintaining a local store of the NEON data you
use. The <code>neonUtilities</code> function
<code>stackFromStore()</code> works with files downloaded by
<code>neonstore</code>. See the
<a href="https://www.neonscience.org/resources/learning-hub/tutorials/neonstore-stackfromstore-tutorial" target="_blank">neonstore
tutorial</a> for more information.</li>
</ol>
<p>Now let’s explore the aquatic plant data. OS data products are simple
in that the data generally tabular, and data volumes are lower than the
other NEON data types, but they are complex in that almost all consist
of multiple tables containing information collected at different times
in different ways. For example, samples collected in the field may be
shipped to a laboratory for analysis. Data associated with the field
collection will appear in one data table, and the analytical results
will appear in another. Complexity in working with OS data usually
involves bringing data together from multiple measurements or scales of
analysis.</p>
<p>As with the IS data, the variables file can tell you more about the
data tables.</p>
<p>OS data products each come with a Data Product User Guide, which can
be downloaded with the data, or accessed from the document library on
the Data Portal, or the
<a href="https://data.neonscience.org/data-products/DP1.20063.001" target="_blank">Product
Details</a> page for the data product. The User Guide is designed to
give a basic introduction to the data product, including a brief summary
of the protocol and descriptions of data format and structure.</p>
</div>
<div id="explore-isotope-data" class="section level3 tabset">
<h3 class="tabset">Explore isotope data</h3>
<p>To get started with the aquatic plant chemistry data, let’s take a
look at carbon isotope ratios in plants across the three sites we
downloaded. The chemical analytes are reported in the
<code>apl_plantExternalLabDataPerSample</code> table, and the table is
in long format, with one record per sample per analyte, so we’ll subset
to only the carbon isotope analyte:</p>
<div id="r-12" class="section level4">
<h4>R</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>boxplot(analyteConcentration~siteID, 
        data=apl_plantExternalLabDataPerSample, 
        subset=analyte==&quot;d13C&quot;,
        xlab=&quot;Site&quot;, ylab=&quot;d13C&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="504" /></p>
</div>
<div id="python-12" class="section level4">
<h4>Python</h4>
<pre class="python"><code>apl13C = apl_plantExternalLabDataPerSample[
         apl_plantExternalLabDataPerSample.analyte==&quot;d13C&quot;]
grouped = apl13C.groupby(&quot;siteID&quot;)[&quot;analyteConcentration&quot;]
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.boxplot(x=[group.values for name, group in grouped],
           tick_labels=grouped.groups.keys())</code></pre>
<pre><code>## {&#39;whiskers&#39;: [&lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b899490&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b899ed0&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8a5bd0&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8a65d0&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8ae5d0&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8aeed0&gt;], &#39;caps&#39;: [&lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b89a9d0&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b89b4d0&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8a70d0&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8a7b50&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8af950&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8b8490&gt;], &#39;boxes&#39;: [&lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b898b90&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8a5190&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8adbd0&gt;], &#39;medians&#39;: [&lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b89be50&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8ac610&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8b8e90&gt;], &#39;fliers&#39;: [&lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8a4950&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8ad090&gt;, &lt;matplotlib.lines.Line2D object at 0x13b8b9990&gt;], &#39;means&#39;: []}</code></pre>
<pre class="python"><code>plt.show()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-12" class="section level3 unnumbered">
<h3 class="unnumbered"></h3>
<p>We see plants at Suggs and Toolik are quite low in 13C, with more
spread at Toolik than Suggs, and plants at Prairie Lake are relatively
enriched. Clearly the next question is what species these data
represent. But taxonomic data aren’t present in the
<code>apl_plantExternalLabDataPerSample</code> table, they’re in the
<code>apl_biomass</code> table. We’ll need to join the two tables to get
chemistry by taxon.</p>
<p>Every NEON data product has a Quick Start Guide (QSG), and for OS
products it includes a section describing how to join the tables in the
data product. Since it’s a pdf file, <code>loadByProduct()</code>
doesn’t bring it in, but you can view the Aquatic plant chemistry QSG on
the
<a href="https://data.neonscience.org/data-products/DP1.20063.001" target="_blank">Product
Details</a> page. The <code>neonOS</code> package uses the information
from the QSGs to provide an automated table-joining function,
<code>joinTableNEON()</code>.</p>
</div>
<div id="explore-isotope-data-by-species" class="section level3 tabset">
<h3 class="tabset">Explore isotope data by species</h3>
<div id="r-13" class="section level4">
<h4>R</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>apct &lt;- joinTableNEON(apl_biomass, 
            apl_plantExternalLabDataPerSample)</code></pre>
<p>Using the merged data, now we can plot carbon isotope ratio for each
taxon.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>boxplot(analyteConcentration~scientificName, 
        data=apct, subset=analyte==&quot;d13C&quot;, 
        xlab=NA, ylab=&quot;d13C&quot;, 
        las=2, cex.axis=0.7)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="504" /></p>
</div>
<div id="python-13" class="section level4">
<h4>Python</h4>
<p>There is not yet an equivalent to the <code>neonOS</code> package in
Python, so we will code the table join manually, based on the info in
the Quick Start Guide:</p>
<pre class="python"><code>
apct = pd.merge(apl_biomass, 
            apl_plantExternalLabDataPerSample,
            left_on=[&quot;siteID&quot;, &quot;chemSubsampleID&quot;],
            right_on=[&quot;siteID&quot;, &quot;sampleID&quot;],
            how=&quot;outer&quot;)</code></pre>
<p>Using the merged data, now we can plot carbon isotope ratio for each
taxon.</p>
<pre class="python"><code>apl13Cspp = apct[apct.analyte==&quot;d13C&quot;]
grouped = apl13Cspp.groupby(&quot;scientificName&quot;)[&quot;analyteConcentration&quot;]
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.boxplot(x=[group.values for name, group in grouped],
           tick_labels=grouped.groups.keys())</code></pre>

<h3 class="unnumbered"></h3>
<p>And now we can see most of the sampled plants have carbon isotope

</div>
<div id="download-remote-sensing-data-byfileaop-and-bytileaop" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2 class="tabset">Download remote sensing data: byFileAOP() and
byTileAOP()</h2>
<p>Remote sensing data files are very large, so downloading them can
take a long time. <code>byFileAOP()</code> and <code>byTileAOP()</code>
enable easier programmatic downloads, but be aware it can take a very
long time to download large amounts of data.</p>
<p>Input options for the AOP functions are:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>dpID</code>: the data product ID, e.g. DP1.00002.001</li>
<li><code>site</code>: the 4-letter code of a single site,
e.g. HARV</li>
<li><code>year</code>: the 4-digit year to download</li>
<li><code>savepath</code>: the file path you want to download to;
defaults to the working directory</li>
<li><code>check.size</code>: T or F: should the function pause before
downloading data and warn you about the size of your download? Defaults
to T; if you are using this function within a script or batch process
you will want to set it to F.</li>
<li><code>easting</code>: <code>byTileAOP()</code> only. Vector of
easting UTM coordinates whose corresponding tiles you want to
download</li>
<li><code>northing</code>: <code>byTileAOP()</code> only. Vector of
northing UTM coordinates whose corresponding tiles you want to
download</li>
<li><code>buffer</code>: <code>byTileAOP()</code> only. Size in meters
of buffer to include around coordinates when deciding which tiles to
download</li>
<li><code>token</code>: Optional NEON API token for faster
downloads.</li>
<li><code>chunk_size</code>: Only in Python. Set the chunk size of
chunked downloads, can improve efficiency in some cases. Defaults to 1
MB.</li>
</ul>
<p>Here, we’ll download one tile of Ecosystem structure (Canopy Height
Model) (DP3.30015.001) from WREF in 2017.</p>
<div id="r-14" class="section level3">
<h3>R</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>byTileAOP(dpID=&quot;DP3.30015.001&quot;, site=&quot;WREF&quot;, 
          year=2017,easting=580000, 
          northing=5075000, 
          savepath=&quot;~/Downloads&quot;)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-14" class="section level3">
<h3>Python</h3>
<pre class="python"><code>nu.by_tile_aop(dpid=&quot;DP3.30015.001&quot;, site=&quot;WREF&quot;, 
               year=2017,easting=580000, 
               northing=5075000, 
               savepath=os.path.expanduser(
                 &quot;~/Downloads&quot;))</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-14" class="section level2 unnumbered">
<h2 class="unnumbered"></h2>
<p>In the directory indicated in <code>savepath</code>, you should now
have a folder named <code>DP3.30015.001</code> with several nested
subfolders, leading to a tif file of a canopy height model tile.</p>
</div>
<div id="navigate-data-downloads-aop" class="section level2 tabset">
<h2 class="tabset">Navigate data downloads: AOP</h2>
<p>To work with AOP data, the best bet in R is the <code>terra</code>
package. It has functionality for most analyses you might want to do. In
Python, we’ll use the rasterio package here; explore NEON remote sensing
tutorials for more guidance.</p>
<p>First let’s read in the tile we downloaded:</p>
<div id="r-15" class="section level3">
<h3>R</h3>
<pre class="r"><code>chm &lt;- rast(&quot;~/Downloads/DP3.30015.001/neon-aop-products/2017/FullSite/D16/2017_WREF_1/L3/DiscreteLidar/CanopyHeightModelGtif/NEON_D16_WREF_DP3_580000_5075000_CHM.tif&quot;)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="python-15" class="section level3">
<h3>Python</h3>
<pre class="python"><code>
chm = rasterio.open(os.path.expanduser(&quot;~/Downloads/DP3.30015.001/neon-aop-products/2017/FullSite/D16/2017_WREF_1/L3/DiscreteLidar/CanopyHeightModelGtif/NEON_D16_WREF_DP3_580000_5075000_CHM.tif&quot;))</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-15" class="section level2 unnumbered">
<h2 class="unnumbered"></h2>
<div id="plot-canopy-height-model" class="section level3 tabset">
<h3 class="tabset">Plot canopy height model</h3>
<div id="r-16" class="section level4">
<h4>R</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>plot(chm, col=topo.colors(6))</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="504" /></p>
</div>
<div id="python-16" class="section level4">
<h4>Python</h4>
<pre class="python"><code>plt.imshow(chm.read(1))
plt.show()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="section-16" class="section level3 unnumbered">
<h3 class="unnumbered"></h3>
<p>Now we can see canopy height across the downloaded tile; the tallest
trees are over 60 meters, not surprising in the Pacific Northwest. There
is a clearing or clear cut in the lower right quadrant.</p>
</div>
</div>
